In article &lt;605@trwind.UUCP&gt; simpson@trwind.trw.com (Scott Simpson) writes:
&gt;In RFC 1065 on SMI, it describes an OBJECT IDENTIFIER tree that looks
&gt;something like
&gt; ...
&gt;This tree is a means to some end.

and then asks "what end?".

Basically, to identify things.  So, to identify a variable, we say
"1.3.2.2.1.2.3", and that identifies a particular variable (with
quotes around it) at some instant of time in some particular SNMP agent
(or other agent using a similar naming scheme).  It is also used
to identify systems (such as "4.3 BSD as distributed by PC vendor X,
release P.Q") and will be used to identify people, companies, etc.  See
a screw, it will someday have an object identifier.

(Clearly, in the above variable case, "1.3.2..." identifies an object
having a certain semantic meaning, and not a specific instance of that
object.  In the case of "4.3 BSD as...", we are again identifying an
object to belong to a certain class.  In the case of people, we are
identifying a specific instance of person.  I'm always a bit fuzzy here.)

There is a schema lying around.  It is included in the MIB and SMI documents
(though only implicitly).

You name a host by "130.57.22.22"; on a host, you name a varialbe by
"1.3.2.2.1.2.3".

Hope this sheds a bit of light.

Greg Minshall			Novell, Inc.
